args:
With her pursuers defeated, Nino resolves to
reject her captive fate. She declines Ryszarda
and Tobias's offers, electing to freely travel the
world instead. Tobias, clad in Nino's armor, sets
off to continue his fight for a happier world.
Ryszarda, Raphael, are you all right?
You don't have to worry about us.
The numbness is finally going away.
It's fine. Just... Exhaustion's hitting me\nnow that the adrenaline's wearing off.
I'll be fine after some rest.\nI've never fought like that before.
It was quite the surprise. I had no idea\nyou wielded such powers.
Neither did I. But apparently my ancestor\nleft me more than that armor and the key.
Oh, I suppose I never mentioned that to\nyou. My body is home to a unique form of\nmana.
I heard from Raphael. That and how your\nmana is required to get at the remaining\nScrolls of Perdition.
When you told me you were a perditionist,\nI decided not to bring it up. I was told they\nwere all desperately searching for me.
Tell me, Tobias: do you also want to\nuse that key and complete the Scrolls?
I'm not fighting for the Scrolls. My only\naim is to incite change with the Church,\nso that more lives can be saved.
I'm more concerned with what I can do to\neffect that change today than what some\ntext may say. As your ancestor wished it.
Huh. You really aren't like the other Church\npeople I've met.
I'm glad you were the one who came to my\nvillage that day, Tobias. Thank you.
Ahem...I do hate to interrupt, but can we\nleave this place?
Right. More pursuers could be on their\nway.
You're a mess, Tobias.\nHere, lean on my shoulder.
What will you do now, Nino?
The Halidom is full of trustworthy allies.\nThey can keep you safe.
I'll swear my own sword to defend you as\nwell—as a single Paladyn who wishes for\nall life to find happiness.
Our true mission is to secure the key to\nperdition. We neglected to mention that in\nhopes of doing this smoothly.
But you really would be comfortable and\nsafe in The Curia. I'll gladly negotiate\nfor your right to come and go from it.
The higher-ups did tell us to force the\nmatter if you declined, but...
But we will respect your choice. If you\ndon't wish to come with us, we'll withdraw.
If not for your bravery,\nwe would both be dead.
We are apostle and angel, executing\nthe divine will of the Goddess.
It cannot be Her wish that we perform our\nduties against the will of our savior.
So it sounds like you DO have a choice.\nAnd all of them are equally valid.
I knew the moment a faerie wing appeared\non my back. The path I choose is—
One week later...\nA cathedral in North Grastaea
So our punishment is pending... Oof.\nCan't say I'm looking forward to THAT.
But our command center's putting in a\nword with the guys upstairs to make sure\nit's nothing TOO harsh.
Eep! Leave it up to you to always\nlook at the bright side, Raphael.
What's wrong with that? Us ＂failing＂ our\nmission means Nino gets to go travel the\nworld.
I suppose so... Still, it surprised me.
I didn't expect her to turn Tobias down,\ntoo.
Oh! You're from the food stall in Peng Lai.\nWere you on your way back there now?
This area is home to dangerous fiends.\nI'll escort you to safety.
You're a Paladyn from the Ilian Church,\nright? Why do all this for somebody who's\nnot even a believer?
The Goddess's will is that ALL people find\nhappiness.
...A sentiment shared by the one who\nentrusted this armor to me.
The perditionists and conservatives will\nhound you still. You're certain you won't\ncome to the Halidom?
I'm not an object in need of protection\nanymore. I'll overcome what troubles\nthe future may bring myself.
I want to travel. To see the world with my\nown two eyes.
Let me return the gem that forms this\narmor to you. It was a charm handed\ndown for your protection.
No. You keep it. I don't think I'm really\nbuilt to wear armor. Plus...
I'm sure my ancestors would rather it be\nused in the fight for a happier world.
(She promised to visit the Halidom as\npart of her travels.)
(Until that day, I'll use this armor to take\nwing in my own way, as best I'm able.)
Hey, why do you think the higher-ups\nwanted the key to perdition in the first\nplace?
That's what's got me stumped, too. They\ndidn't exactly give an explanation along\nwith their orders.
They have no reason to care about some\nthousand-year-old truth. It was all passed\ndown to the Northern Church anyway.
What need could they have to track down\nthe remaining portions of the Scrolls?
Unless...the Scrolls of Perdition hold more\nthan just that truth.
The battle amongst the churches for the Goddess's\nscion came to an end, for now.
The circumstances of Nino's bloodline remain\nunchanged. Yet she will continue on undeterred.
(The birds have all the sky above to roam,\nbut I could only watch them.)
(Yet now I have a wing of my own.)
(A fine gift, bequeathed by my ancestor...\nOne to grant me the sky, and to improve\nthe world below it.)
Now... Where shall I fly today?
